    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix potential hang in gaussdouble() when called without initialization\n\n### Summary\nThe `gaussdouble()` function in the random number generation library can hang indefinitely when called without first calling `randominit()`. This occurs because the underlying `uniformrandom()` function returns 0.0 when uninitialized, causing the Box-Muller transformation to loop forever.\n\nThis fix adds initialization checks that will abort with a clear error message if the function is used without proper initialization.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/SIMULATION/TOOLS/rangen_double.c`: \n  - Added `uniformRandomInitDone` flag to track initialization state\n  - Set flag to true in `randominit()`\n  - Added initialization checks to `gaussdouble()` and `uniformrandom()` functions\n  - Used same pattern as existing `gaussZiggurat()` function for consistency\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Call `gaussdouble(0.0, 1.0)` without first calling `randominit()`\n2. Observe that the program hangs indefinitely\n3. With this fix, the program will abort with error message: \"gaussdouble(): RNG not initialized, run randominit() first\"\n\nThe fix maintains backward compatibility for correctly written code that calls `randominit()` before using the random number generators.\n"
}